<h2 style="color: #663300; background: #fff3cd; padding: 10px; border-left: 8px solid #ffa000; border-radius: 6px;">ğŸ’» Python Code</h2>
<pre style="background-color: #fffaf0; color: #4b2e00; padding: 16px; border-radius: 10px; border: 1px solid #ffe0b2; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.5; overflow-x: auto;"><code># Simulate daily temperature vs. monthly average
daily_temps = [32, 30, 29, 31, 33, 28, 27]
monthly_avg = sum(daily_temps) / len(daily_temps)
print(f"Daily temps: {daily_temps}")
print(f"Monthly average (climate indicator): {monthly_avg:.1f}&deg;C")
</code></pre>
<h2 style="color: #663300; background: #fff3cd; padding: 10px; border-left: 8px solid #ffa000; border-radius: 6px;">ğŸ“¤ Sample Output</h2>
<pre style="background: #fffdf5; padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ffe0b2; border-radius: 8px; font-size: 1em;">Daily temps: [32, 30, 29, 31, 33, 28, 27]
Monthly average (climate indicator): 30.0&deg;C
</pre>
<h2 style="color: #663300; background: #fff3cd; padding: 10px; border-left: 8px solid #ffa000; border-radius: 6px;">ğŸ§© Think and Decide</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>If today is 35 &deg;C and tomorrow is 22 &deg;C, is that climate change?</strong><br />Answer: No &ndash; that&rsquo;s weather, because climate needs decades of data.</li>
<li><strong>Why might two neighbouring towns have different climates?</strong><br />Answer: Factors like altitude, proximity to sea, or topography differ.</li>
<li><strong>How many years of data would you need to gather to describe the climate?</strong><br />Answer: At least 30 years, as per meteorological standards.</li>
</ul>
